Little Rock was an important city in the Trans - Mississippi Department of the Confederate States of America during the American Civil War. It was the site of the state government and was located along the Arkansas River, which was an important transportation artery for the state. The city was defended by the Confederate Army's Department of the Trans - Mississippi, which was responsible for the defense of the state and the river.
Little Rock was captured by Union forces on September 10, 1863, after a prolonged siege and bombardment. The city remained under Union control for the remainder of the war. Although the city was in Union hands, there were still many Confederate sympathizers who lived in the area, and there were occasional incidents of guerrilla warfare and sabotage. After the war, Little Rock was rebuilt and continued to grow and develop as a major city in Arkansas. Today, it is the state capital and a thriving metropolis with a population of over 200,000 people. } }
